column10:
It lives up to its "souls-esque" description in both a great way (aesthetics and themes of pain and redemption through suffering) and, in my opinion, the worst way possible: by fighting you and bending the rules to its convenience. I've  found myself both annoyed by the repetitive strategies (approach, slash, retreat/parry, rinse and repeat every time you need to go somewhere) needed to defeat most enemies and underwhelmed by the tools the game put a my disposal. Unavoidable and space filling attacks don't make me feel tested, they make me feel cheated and lied to.  
After getting to the final boss and losing all my will to proceed, I can now complete the review.
Though the themes remain interesting, the game did not stimulate me enough to try and complete it fully. the feeling to increasing distrust and annoyance (especially the 3 part combo near the end) just made the whole experience feel undercooked and in need of more time to mature. Grandiose words and dialog, promise of great things to come and, in the end, great disappointment with some good-ish experiences in the middle.

Summary:
Things I enjoyed:

- the themes and their visual representations. Though they could use a bit more relation between visual and verbal references;

- about half the mechanics. The prayers and, especially, the relics, were very interesting, flavourful and I felt they were decently used in the exploration of the map (though the free falling veil could become more of a nuisance when trying to overcome an enemy that would propel me 2 floors down);

- the music. Apart form the track used in the Silent Path (it evoked too much the track used in the area Deepnest in "Hollow Knight".

Tings I was not so happy about:

- the slight hitches, such as: getting perma-stunned by an enemy, the way the platforms would at times not respond to the character being on top of them, especially when jumping onto them,;

- the way the different teleportation systems in the game felt disjointed and not complimentary;

Spend money to spend time feeling the fucking pain!

The only advantage: the art of some scenes is really eye-catching.

A whole bunch of disadvantages:

The traces of deliberate torture are too obvious, and other games will at most let you get stuck, jumping/chopping/solving puzzles over and over again. The biggest feature of this game is that a considerable part of the difficulty lies in the platform jumping; Make a mistake once, die on the spot, and possibly start again from a distant rebirth point;

Traps are a one-hit for players, and the game production team has designed traps in front of almost every seemingly important item;

The character operation is too stiff and weird, and the climbing judgment is also very strange, resulting in the inability to dodge the difficulties of various maps, many times you see that the character's feet have been significantly higher than the floor of the scene but just can't go up, go to the edge of the floor The character will automatically hang on the edge, in this case, the game production team actually did a lot of map traps, very disappointed, I really feel that the game production team did this to deliberately extend the player's play time;

If you don't donate 20,000 to the church and you're going somewhere, there's a good chance you'll have to walk for minutes to get there after leaving the teleportation point, and don't forget the character operation I just mentioned, you may have to spend more time.

This game has linkage content with Bloodstained: Ritual of the Night, but this linkage content has no combat content, its content is actually platform jumping, as I said before, the character operation is too stiff and weird, and the climbing judgment is also very strange, it actually uses platform jumping as the content, with the game production team designed the trap and strange map design that will die at the first contact, you will find that the game production team is a group of psychopaths.

Try your best to torture you, and the few items that you have painstakingly obtained are useless, the battle has an upper limit and no lower limit, 35 hours completely do not appreciate what this game has to play, what is interesting, what excites you, blindly imitating the difficulty of DARK SOULS but not learning the rich combat system of others, this game is full of malice, difficult for the sake of difficulty, disgusting your valleys and spikes everywhere and the terrain that will die if you make a mistake, The damage received by the character when colliding with the enemy is equivalent to receiving complete damage, the miscellaneous soldiers who will hide after a fight are still fucking high in health and take multiple attacks, and skills that are unnecessary but cost a lot of fucking money to buy, and skill upgrades are also monotonous and tedious.
